00:18:22,200 --> 00:18:28,400
 block we get 24 and 3/4 centimetres. From H2 to the bust point which is part of the

201
00:18:28,400 --> 00:18:35,720
 bust line is 9 and a half centimetres. Therefore 24 and 3/4 minus 9 and a half centimetres is

202
00:18:35,720 --> 00:18:41,440
 15 and a quarter centimetres and that's the remainder we need from the bust point out.

203
00:18:41,440 --> 00:18:47,320
 So I'll measure from the bust point towards and through point K for 15 and a quarter centimetres

204
00:18:47,320 --> 00:18:53,640
 and mark point K2. While it does look very angular on the block I have just placed those

205
00:18:53,640 --> 00:18:58,680
 exact lines on Dee Dee's twile and on the twile it doesn't look angular. The bust is

206
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:04,280
 actually a curve but those straight lines are good enough for fitting purposes. Now if

207
00:19:04,280 --> 00:19:08,800
 you have a large bust chances are that that line will look even more angular. There's

208
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:13,960
 a straight line from the centre front to the bust point but then it goes way up on an angle.

209
00:19:13,960 --> 00:19:18,240
 On my body form it actually looks straight and parallel to the floor. On my body it's

210
00:19:18,240 --> 00:19:22,200
 actually angled up a bit but that's because I've put on weight and the block that fits

211
00:19:22,200 --> 00:19:26,440
 my body form doesn't fit me so well at the moment.

212
00:19:26,440 --> 00:19:30,640
 So the next measurement is the side length number 9 on the measurement chart. We'll

213
00:19:30,640 --> 00:19:35,020
 draw the side seam and in the process we'll get the side seam angle that will give us

214
00:19:35,020 --> 00:19:41,480
 our bust cup. So taking your side seam length measurement measure from point J through

215
00:19:41,480 --> 00:19:49,120
 point K2 in a straight line and at the end of that measurement mark point L.

216
00:19:49,120 --> 00:19:54,480
 Moving up to the across chest measurement which is number 22 on the chart. You usually measure

217
00:19:54,480 --> 00:19:59,480
 from armhole to armhole and divide by 2. Now when you measure the across chest you should

218
00:19:59,480 --> 00:20:04,600
 have noted the depth where you took that measurement how far down from the centre front you took

219
00:20:04,600 --> 00:20:10,320
 that measurement. For the milage about 2/3 of the way down from the centre front neck

220
00:20:10,320 --> 00:20:17,040
 and the upper bust is a good place. I took it a little bit lower than that for DD. Now

221
00:20:17,040 --> 00:20:21,880
 using the across chest measurement measure inwards from the centre front line and at

222
00:20:21,880 --> 00:20:27,720
 right angles to the centre front line and mark point M.

223
00:20:27,720 --> 00:20:33,480
 We will draw the armhole next but first we'll just draw a guideline to assist in that. We

224
00:20:33,480 --> 00:20:39,080
 don't want to dip below this line when drawing the curve. So from J draw a guideline for

225
00:20:39,080 --> 00:20:45,320
 about 8 centimetres and that line has to be at right angles to the side seam. Mark the

226
00:20:45,320 --> 00:20:52,320
 end point J2. Taking a French curve draw the armhole from the shoulder point G to touch

227
00:20:52,320 --> 00:20:59,120
 the across chest point M and finishing at point J at the underarm upper bust. Now this

228
00:20:59,120 --> 00:21:04,920
 block currently has no ease so that armhole curve is for the milage.

229
00:21:04,920 --> 00:21:10,400
 So now the neck line curve. Taking the French curve again draw a line from point I at the

230
00:21:10,400 --> 00:21:18,280
 high neck and down to point E at the centre front. Now don't dip below the E to E2 line

231
00:21:18,280 --> 00:21:25,800
 however you can cut into the E to E2 line. Now with DD her neck curve the pink line does

232
00:21:25,800 --> 00:21:31,600
 not cut into that E to E2 line but the green line shows how standard shaping works for

233
00:21:31,600 --> 00:21:36,600
 the neck line. Now I will show you in the next slide on my block because in this regard

234
00:21:36,600 --> 00:21:43,640
 I am standard and DD is not. So I have enlarged my block and you can just see the top of it

235
00:21:43,640 --> 00:21:49,800
 and this is my neck line curve. For my curve it goes in a quarter of a centimetre beyond

236
00:21:49,800 --> 00:21:55,160
 the E to E2 line and this is actually what a lot of block making instructions say for

237
00:21:55,160 --> 00:22:01,040
 the standard body so it seems that I am standard in this regard the shape of my neck whereas

238
00:22:01,040 --> 00:22:08,080
 DD is not standard. Now we will do the waist. First we will place the first dart leg. Measure

239
00:22:08,080 --> 00:22:14,880
 from point H2 to the bust point. Take that measurement and subtract 2 centimetres. Using

240
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:23,760
 the total measure on the waist line from point A towards point D and mark point N. Now draw

241
00:22:23,760 --> 00:22:30,160
 a line from the bust point through point N and a quarter of a centimetre past point N.

242
00:22:30,160 --> 00:22:35,640
 Mark point N2. The reason for extending the dart leg below the waist is to get a curve

243
00:22:35,640 --> 00:22:39,200
 for the waist rather than a straight line and you will see how that works at the end when

244
00:22:39,200 --> 00:22:47,120
 we do the waist shaping. Now draw a guideline from point L at the side seam to point N2,

245
00:22:47,120 --> 00:22:52,440
 the first dart leg. This is our waistline or part of our waistline because A to N2 is

246
00:22:52,440 --> 00:22:59,200
 also part of the waistline but we need to determine how much of this L to N2 is access

247
00:22:59,200 --> 00:23:05,440
 to requirements and put the excess into the dart. So take your waist measurement and divide

248
00:23:05,440 --> 00:23:12,680
 it by 4. We will call this value X. Now measure from point A to point N2 and we will call

249
00:23:12,680 --> 00:23:21,880
 that value Y. Take X and subtract Y, giving us the value of Z or Z if you are American.

250
00:23:21,880 --> 00:23:26,840
 Using the value of Z, measure from point L at the side seam along that guideline that

251
00:23:26,840 --> 00:23:33,720
 you have just drawn and mark point O. Now measure the first dart leg from the bust

252
00:23:33,720 --> 00:23:39,800
 point to N2. We need to make our second dart leg the same length. So draw the second dart

253
00:23:39,800 --> 00:23:48,040
 leg from the bust point through point O and mark point O2. Now draw a line from point L

254
00:23:48,040 --> 00:23:52,720
 to point O2. At the moment we are drawing a straight line but we will later make that

255
00:23:52,720 --> 00:23:58,840
 a bit curved. We will do that at the end after we have converted it to a two dart block.

256
00:23:58,840 --> 00:24:03,240
 Now the main shape of the block is finished. That is without any ease and we actually

257
00:24:03,240 --> 00:24:07,280
 have not drawn in the waistline properly. We will finish the waistline curve later when

258
00:24:07,280 --> 00:24:11,700
 we make it a two dart block. So we want to add two and a half centimetres

259
00:24:11,700 --> 00:24:17,000
 ease in the waist across the whole block, which is a bit hard to divide evenly. We will

260
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:22,160
 add one centimetre ease to the front and one and a half to the back. For the half front

261
00:24:22,160 --> 00:24:28,760
 that is half a centimetre. So measure half a centimetre from point L as a continuation

262
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:36,120
 of the O2 to L line and mark point L2. This is the waist side seam point for the sleeveless

263
00:24:36,120 --> 00:24:41,760
 and the standard block. Now we will add ease at the upper bust for the sleeveless block.

264
00:24:41,760 --> 00:24:47,720
 We will also lower the armhole one and a half centimetres. The upper bust ease for the sleeveless

265
00:24:47,720 --> 00:24:52,280
 block is seven and a half centimetres across the whole block. We will add two thirds of

266
00:24:52,280 --> 00:24:57,840
 that to the back and one third to the front. So we will add five centimetres to the back

267
00:24:57,840 --> 00:25:04,080
 and two and a half centimetres to the front. For the half front that is 1.25 centimetres

268
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:11,160
 ease. Note that the J to L side seam line is the muleage side seam line. So measure down

269
00:25:11,160 --> 00:25:18,000
 on the J to L muleage side seam line for one and a half centimetres to lower the armhole.

270
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:24,360
 Then measure out from that point and at right angles to the muleage side seam line for one

271
00:25:24,360 --> 00:25:31,440
 point two five centimetres and mark point J3. Now draw a line which will be the sleeveless

272
00:25:31,440 --> 00:25:38,160
 block side seam line from point J3 towards and through point L2 at the waist. Make the

273
00:25:38,160 --> 00:25:45,280
 length of that line your body side seam length minus 1.5 centimetres. Mark the end of that

274
00:25:45,280 --> 00:25:53,160
 line point L3. Now finish the armhole curve for the sleeveless block using a French curve.

275
00:25:53,160 --> 00:25:56,960
 You generally need a little bit of a straight line to begin with at the underarm so that

276
00:25:56,960 --> 00:26:01,120
 you get a smooth curve between the back and the front when they are joined but just draw

277
00:26:01,120 --> 00:26:09,840
 a curve from point J3 to blend at point M at a cross chest. The purple stroke line is

278
00:26:09,840 --> 00:26:15,640
 the muleage outline and the blue stroke line is the sleeveless block. The muleage is drawn

279
00:26:15,640 --> 00:26:20,640
 from point G at the shoulder to point J at the underarm. The muleage side seam is from

280
00:26:20,640 --> 00:26:27,120
 point J to point L at the waist then to point O2 at the waist dart line. The sleeveless

281
00:26:27,120 --> 00:26:33,000
 block is from point G at the shoulder to point J3 at the underarm to point L3 at the side

282
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:38,360
 waist and then to point O2 at the waist dart line. The ease for the sleeveless block is

283
00:26:38,360 --> 00:26:42,800
 highlighted in yellow. Of course this is the half front so there is the same amount on

284
00:26:42,800 --> 00:26:48,800
 the other side plus there's the ease in the back. Now we'll draw in the side seam for

285
00:26:48,800 --> 00:26:54,040
 the standard block to be used with sleeves so we'll add some ease and also lower the

286
00:26:54,040 --> 00:27:00,480
 arm hole a little. Ease for the standard block is usually 12 and a half centimetres in the

287
00:27:00,480 --> 00:27:05,840
 upper bust. If you are wondering about this amount of ease and think it may be too much

288
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:11,280
 I suggest you watch my video on ease as part of the bodice block essentials where I show

289
00:27:11,280 --> 00:27:16,760
 that this is the standard amount at the upper bust for the standard block. Just note though

290
00:27:16,760 --> 00:27:21,560
 that we are adding this at the upper bust there will be less ease in the bust. If you

291
00:27:21,560 --> 00:27:26,320
 have a look you can see the wedge of ease in the sleeveless block narrows as it moves

292
00:27:26,320 --> 00:27:32,760
 toward the waist. There is less ease in the bust than there is in the upper bust. So 12

293
00:27:32,760 --> 00:27:37,680
 and a half centimetres ease but as we're using the sleeveless block as our starting point

294
00:27:37,680 --> 00:27:43,480
 and we've already added 7 and a half centimetres there we need 5 centimetres more. A third

295
00:27:43,480 --> 00:27:48,800
 of that to the front two thirds to the back. This works out at 1.6 centimetres for the

296
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:54,520
 front. Half that and round it down slightly and we end up with three quarters of a centimetre

297
00:27:54,520 --> 00:28:00,360
 ease extra for the front. So first we'll lower the arm hole one centimetre measuring down

298
00:28:00,360 --> 00:28:06,720
 the J3 to L3 sleeveless side seam line for three quarters of a centimetre. Mark point

299
00:28:06,720 --> 00:28:12,600
 J5. Draw a line from J5 at the underarm to point L3 at the waist. This is the side seam

300
00:28:12,600 --> 00:28:18,280
 line for the standard or block to be used with sleeves. Before drawing the arm hole for the

301
00:28:18,280 --> 00:28:24,000
 sleeveled block we'll add a bit to both the shoulder length and the across chest measurements.

302
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:29,160
 There is some ease added for sleeve movement. Extend the shoulder line from point G by one

303
00:28:29,160 --> 00:28:36,000
 centimetre and mark point G2. Then extend the across chest line past point M for a half centimetre

304
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:42,120
 and mark point M2. Using a French curve draw a line to draw the arm hole for the sleeve

305
00:28:42,120 --> 00:28:48,400
 block from G2 through M2 and to touch point J5 at the underarm. You may not be able to

306
00:28:48,400 --> 00:28:53,560
 draw it in one path. You may have to draw two lines and blend them. The green shaded

307
00:28:53,560 --> 00:28:59,480
 bit shows what we've added to the sleeve block. Now we can measure how much ease we have ended

308
00:28:59,480 --> 00:29:04,240
 up with at the bus level for the front here and when we draft the back we can check the

309
00:29:04,240 --> 00:29:09,800
 back amount and add it together. You should end up with somewhere between 5 to 7 centimetres

310
00:29:09,800 --> 00:29:15,720
 ease for the sleeveless block and about 7.5 or 8.5 centimetres ease for the block with

311
00:29:15,720 --> 00:29:21,080
 sleeves. That's the total across the whole block. If when you make your 12 this is too

312
00:29:21,080 --> 00:29:27,920
 much then shave a little bit off the wedge front and back for both either the sleeveless

313
00:29:27,920 --> 00:29:32,880
 and the sleeve block if that's what you want to do. If you do that make sure you taper

314
00:29:32,880 --> 00:29:38,760
 it down to point L3 at the waist. The way we're going to convert this into a 2 dart block

315
00:29:38,760 --> 00:29:44,040
 is by cutting and spreading. First draw a guideline below the waistline and parallel

316
00:29:44,040 --> 00:29:50,120
 to it that is half a centimetre below the waistline. You can see that on the left most

317
00:29:50,120 --> 00:29:56,160
 image. Still looking at the image on the left from the side seam cut along the bust line

318
00:29:56,160 --> 00:30:02,080
 to the bust point. Then cut up through the left waist dart leg to the bust point but

319
00:30:02,080 --> 00:30:07,400
 leave a hinge don't separate that piece completely. In the second image I've coloured that cut

320
00:30:07,400 --> 00:30:13,540
 piece in yellow so it's easy to see what's going on. That piece is pivoted down pivoted

321
00:30:13,540 --> 00:30:20,040
 on the hinge left at the bust point so that the side seam touches the line below the waist.

322
00:30:20,040 --> 00:30:24,360
 On the right I'm showing you that you need to put paper underneath the opened up section

323
00:30:24,360 --> 00:30:31,180
 and stick it down. That opened up section is the side seam dart and the waist dart has

324
00:30:31,180 --> 00:30:38,720
 reduced in size and the blue lines show that what the waist dart is now. On the left side

325
00:30:38,720 --> 00:30:43,320
 is what we ended up with on the last slide. In the middle graphic you can see that I've

326
00:30:43,320 --> 00:30:47,880
 just drawn straight lines to close both of the darts. We will finish off the darts in

327
00:30:47,880 --> 00:30:52,520
 the next slide but I'll be working with the white copy on the end so that it's less busy

328
00:30:52,520 --> 00:30:57,360
 less distractions. Again I'll be working with just the sleeveless block but the method

329
00:30:57,360 --> 00:31:03,240
 is the same for any dart. So now we'll finish off the shaping of the side seam dart. As

330
00:31:03,240 --> 00:31:08,520
 shown in the example A locate the middle of the side seam dart and draw a guard line from

331
00:31:08,520 --> 00:31:14,640
 the bust point through that point. As shown in example B continue to straight line from

332
00:31:14,640 --> 00:31:20,000
 the armhole past the top dart leg to touch that mid dart line. That is a straight line

333
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:26,920
 from the under arm point to touch the mid dart line. Then as shown in C draw a line from

334
00:31:26,920 --> 00:31:32,740
 the bottom dart leg to meet that previous point. In this case it will not be or it probably

335
00:31:32,740 --> 00:31:39,080
 won't be a continuation of the line from the waist. Finishing it off this way will

336
00:31:39,080 --> 00:31:44,240
 mean that it will fall downwards and the edges will be flush. If you want to fold it upwards

337
00:31:44,240 --> 00:31:49,000
 which is not usual you do it the opposite way. As in you continue the line from the waist

338
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:53,680
 upwards a straight line in continuation of the side seam upwards to meet the mid dart

339
00:31:53,680 --> 00:31:59,200
 line. Then you draw a line from the top dart leg to meet that point. In this case that

340
00:31:59,200 --> 00:32:04,960
 line downwards will not be a continuation of the line from the under arm point. Now you

341
00:32:04,960 --> 00:32:10,040
 could alternatively just fold the paper by which I mean you close the dart on the paper

342
00:32:10,040 --> 00:32:16,960
 and then you cut away the excess. I hate folding paper I prefer to use this method.

343
00:32:16,960 --> 00:32:22,360
 Now on the left is the last image from the last slide. In the middle is the final shape

344
00:32:22,360 --> 00:32:29,360
 of the block including those lines from C. Now on the right is my block to show you how

345
00:32:29,360 --> 00:32:34,200
 different it will look with a bigger bust and a bigger side seam dart. But the shaping

346
00:32:34,200 --> 00:32:39,200
 was done the same. The side seam line is continued from the armhole in a straight line to the

347
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:45,480
 mid dart. Then a line is drawn up from the bottom dart leg to meet that previous point.

348
00:32:45,480 --> 00:32:50,480
 The shaping done this way means that the dart will close downwards towards the waist not

349
00:32:50,480 --> 00:32:57,560
 up towards the armhole. Generally you don't want darts to close upwards towards the armhole

350
00:32:57,560 --> 00:33:01,440
 because that creates a little pocket there so for when you do the washing you can catch

351
00:33:01,440 --> 00:33:06,920
 fluff in there etc. I suppose you could catch it downwards too but that would fall out.

352
00:33:06,920 --> 00:33:14,120
 But anyway side seam darts tend to fold down towards the waist. Just another note the green

353
00:33:14,120 --> 00:33:19,920
 dashed lines on my block is the waist shaping done to fold upwards. So the line is drawn

354
00:33:19,920 --> 00:33:23,840
 from the waist first to meet the mid dart line and then the second line is drawn from

355
00:33:23,840 --> 00:33:30,440
 the top dart leg to meet that point. Now for the waist shaping as shown in image

356
00:33:30,440 --> 00:33:35,880
 one find the mid dart point again the waist dart the middle of it and draw a line from

357
00:33:35,880 --> 00:33:40,280
 the bust point through the mid dart point. Remember that we drop the dart legs for three

358
00:33:40,280 --> 00:33:45,960
 sixteenths of an inch and we also drop the side seam point earlier as well. So we want

359
00:33:45,960 --> 00:33:53,200
 a gentle curve for the waist using a French curve. Look at figure two and make the first

360
00:33:53,200 --> 00:33:57,840
 part of the waistline from the centre front completely straight for a little bit. We want

361
00:33:57,840 --> 00:34:02,240
 that to be at a right angle. We don't want to dip or a valley at the centre front at

362
00:34:02,240 --> 00:34:09,560
 the waistline but curve it down to the dart leg point and continue that curve till it

363
00:34:09,560 --> 00:34:16,280
 touches the mid dart line. Then turn flip flip the French curve over so you've got

364
00:34:16,280 --> 00:34:21,880
 a reflected curve and curve that line back up again. You also want there to be a right

365
00:34:21,880 --> 00:34:27,280
 angle at the side seam so that it will true better with the back block that's shown by

366
00:34:27,280 --> 00:34:35,320
 that blue square showing that that side seam point there is squared. On the left is an

367
00:34:35,320 --> 00:34:40,880
 example of how the waistline would look after the dart was closed if we didn't do that

368
00:34:40,880 --> 00:34:48,600
 curving and the image on the right shows you why we do that curving. In this slide I'm

369
00:34:48,600 --> 00:34:53,160
 showing you that the curve I drew gives a nice flow through at the side seam from the

370
00:34:53,160 --> 00:34:59,280
 back block to the front. The last thing to do is pull the dart points back a little bit

371
00:34:59,280 --> 00:35:04,680
 from the bust point. The bigger the bust the bigger the size the further away generally

372
00:35:04,680 --> 00:35:09,720
 the dart point is from the bust point. A general guide or a starting point is given here on

373
00:35:09,720 --> 00:35:13,240
 the screen. You'll probably need to pause and have a look I'm not going to read all

374
00:35:13,240 --> 00:35:18,760
 of those out. Now these are only general guides and only go up to a decup. Maybe you could

375
00:35:18,760 --> 00:35:23,840
 look at your clothes and measure how far away your dart points are from your apex that is

376
00:35:23,840 --> 00:35:29,160
 assuming that the dart points on your clothes suit your body. Measure along the mid dart

377
00:35:29,160 --> 00:35:36,080
 line away from the bust point and place the new dart point on the mid dart line and redraw

378
00:35:36,080 --> 00:35:43,520
 your darts. I recommend you draw all the lines from the block on the twile. Doing this means

379
00:35:43,520 --> 00:35:49,000
 you can see where you've made mistakes and also it's much easier to see where the adjustments

380
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:55,160
 need to be made. From here on is some general information on truing the front and the back

381
00:35:55,160 --> 00:35:59,480
 and finishing off your block. You need to do this after drafting both the front and the

382
00:35:59,480 --> 00:36:05,480
 back. I'm not using the block I drafted for Didi in these following slides. I'm using

383
00:36:05,480 --> 00:36:11,480
 a standard block. When we finish both the front and the back we need to check that the lengths

384
00:36:11,480 --> 00:36:18,600
 of adjacent pieces match and also check that there is a nice flow through in the curves.

385
00:36:18,600 --> 00:36:23,960
 If you need to increase the length of anything you may need to stick on little bits of paper.

386
00:36:23,960 --> 00:36:30,200
 I'm not going to be doing that in my example but just be aware you may have to. So firstly

387
00:36:30,200 --> 00:36:36,360
 we'll do the side seam. Put the back and front blocks together at the side seam waist. Check

388
00:36:36,360 --> 00:36:43,320
 that there's a smooth curve at the waist. Then check the side seam length. Firstly from

389
00:36:43,320 --> 00:36:49,240
 the waist up to the dart leg. Then check that the remainder matches up. Check that there

390
00:36:49,240 --> 00:36:56,280
 is a smooth curve through the armhole. Then match the front and back at the high neck point to check

391
00:36:56,280 --> 00:37:03,240
 the neckline curve. While you're there mark the shoulder dart placement from the back block onto

392
00:37:03,240 --> 00:37:09,640
 the front block so that you can check the shoulder length. Move the front block to the other dart

393
00:37:09,640 --> 00:37:15,000
 leg and check the shoulder lengths are the same. This is especially important when drafting the

394
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:20,280
 three options together the melage and the sleeveless and the sleeve you may have traced off the sleeveless

395
00:37:20,280 --> 00:37:25,240
 block on the front and then accidentally trace off the sleeve version in the back. So definitely

396
00:37:25,240 --> 00:37:31,720
 always check your shoulder lengths match. Then check the flow through curve of the armhole.

397
00:37:31,720 --> 00:37:38,120
 When you have your final front and back blocks don't forget to mark and notch the dart legs.

398
00:37:38,120 --> 00:37:43,480
 Label the block. Put all the relevant information on it maybe including the date you drafted it.

399
00:37:44,200 --> 00:37:47,720
 Note whether it's a sleeveless block or the sleeve block or the melage.

400
00:37:47,720 --> 00:37:52,440
 Now I did hear a pattern maker say that you don't put the grainline on the block.

401
00:37:52,440 --> 00:37:57,480
 You put that on the pattern but I like to have it on my block to remind me to put it on the pattern.

402
00:37:57,480 --> 00:38:02,200
 Sometimes I forget and then I get to putting my pattern pieces on the fabric and realize I

403
00:38:02,200 --> 00:38:08,120
 haven't drawn the grainline on there. So yes I definitely prefer to put the grainline on the block

404
00:38:08,120 --> 00:38:16,440
 as a reminder. So here are some final blocks not DDs but this is what the final blocks look like.

405
00:38:16,440 --> 00:38:22,600
 These ones don't have the bust line or upper bust mark. That was needed during the drafting process

406
00:38:22,600 --> 00:38:28,120
 for making the twile and getting the measurements right. On the actual blocks you don't need them.

